Diagnosis. This species is unusually distinctive. Both sexes share an unusually curved galea, which, when stored, is ventrally concave ( Fig. 46A ). The scape is ventrally obscured in both sexes, covered in white setae. This is also the smallest species of A . (
Micranthophora
), with females only rarely exceeding 8 mm in body length and males yet smaller. Males of this species are otherwise identifiable by the sharply triangular and concaved pygidial structure on T7, which is closely flanked on each side by a very minute spike ( Fig. 61A ). Females are otherwise identifiable by the highly protuberant clypeus, which from below appears nearly squared with slightly rounded corners ( Fig 41A ). Further, the sides of the pygidial plate are deeply and obviously concave.

Male description.
Head: Facial maculations creamy white. Galea unusually recurved, appearing concave in repose (
Fig. 56A
); reaching about middle of foretrochanter at most; orangish-brown; moderately to weakly tessellate, with some weak reflections. Mandible with inferior tooth absent; maculated for about three-fourths of length (
Fig. 51A
). Labral rim rounded; fully maculated. Clypeal maculation highly variable and sometimes nearly absent, typically a band, not reaching lateral sides, usually filling about half of clypeal height or less medially (
Fig. 51A
); punctation significantly sparser within maculation than without, though denser along rim. Paraocular area immaculate. Supraclypeal area immaculate. Scape immaculate; with many setae covering underside. Mesosoma: Scutum shiny; with distinct impunctate areas. Tegula transparent, orangish to light brown. Basitibial plate absent. Metasoma: T1–T6 covered in appressed setae. Terga smooth between punctures, with strong reflections; usually apparent through appressed setae. Tergal rims transparent, clear. Male T7 (
Fig. 61A
) without medial longitudinal carina; lateral projections easily missed, slight corners; medial projections very short and sharp, split medially by dorsally concave, triangular plate. Male S5 (
Figs. 38A, 38C
) setal arrangement unremarkable, without large, distinctive patches, at most longer along rim. Male S6 (
Fig. 38A
) clearly medially emarginate. Male S7 (
Fig. 66A
) with setae absent or nearly so around midpoint of length; parallel-sided from midpoint to pointed lateral tips; apical half rectangular overall, rim rounded outward. Male S8 (
Fig. 71A
) lateral projections absent; medial projection narrowing to tip, nearly entire at narrow apex. Male genital capsule (
Fig. 76A
) with outer corners, where gonocoxite tips curve inward, marked by distinct and rounded ventral point, best seen in profile; from corner to apex, in profile, gonocoxite relatively unmodified, concave or straight; tip, in profile, rounded and weakly curved ventrally; gonostylus tip position significantly exceeding that of gonocoxite, measured from above along primary axis of latter. Pubescence: See 
Fig. 56A
. Appears white to light gray overall, uncommonly yellowed dorsally. Setae white, except as follows: leg inner faces orange;

